Normal Distribution & Normality Test

1. Run the following code to generate a sample of size 50 from the Student t distribution with degree of freedom 30, and then:

  • generate a histogram of sample x;
  • calculate its summary statistics (min, Q1, median, mean, Q3, max);
  • generate a Q-Q plot with 95% CI for sample x;
  • run Shapiro-Wilk normality test on sample x.
set.seed(57)
x <- rt(n=50,df=30)

Solution: 

hist(x, breaks=15)

summary(x)
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
## -2.14200 -0.91750  0.03698 -0.06852  0.60500  2.11500
car::qqPlot(x)

shapiro.test(x)
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  x
## W = 0.96843, p-value = 0.1996

2. Run normality test on diastolic blood pressure (DIABP) in DIG data for female patients only.

Solution: 

hist(DIABP[SEX==2], breaks=15)

summary(DIABP[SEX==2])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   25.00   70.00   75.00   74.95   80.00  150.00       2
car::qqPlot(DIABP[SEX==2])

shapiro.test(DIABP[SEX==2])
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  DIABP[SEX == 2]
## W = 0.96502, p-value < 2.2e-16

Two-sample T-test & Wilcoxon Rank Sum Test

3. Choose an appropriate test to compare the diastolic blood pressure of the two gender groups in DIG data.

Solution: 

wilcox.test(DIABP~SEX)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  DIABP by SEX
## W = 3996700, p-value = 0.9208
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
summary(DIABP[SEX==1])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   38.00   70.00   75.00   74.89   80.00  184.00       3
summary(DIABP[SEX==2])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##   25.00   70.00   75.00   74.95   80.00  150.00       2

4. Run the following simulation code first and then choose an appropriate test to compare the mean of sample x1 and x2.

set.seed(57)
x1 <- rnorm(100, 2.2, 1)
x2 <- rnorm(100, 2.0, 1)

Solution: 

t.test(x1, x2)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x1 and x2
## t = 1.6841, df = 197.22, p-value = 0.09375
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.04446831  0.56455479
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  2.236611  1.976568

Pearson Correlation

5. Run an appropriate test to see if heart rate (HEARTRTE) is linearly associated with body mass index (BMI) in DIG data.

Solution: 

cor.test(HEARTRTE, BMI)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  HEARTRTE and BMI
## t = 2.2844, df = 6789, p-value = 0.02238
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.003932509 0.051465127
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## 0.02771448

6. Run the following simulation first and then test linear association between x and y.

set.seed(1234)
r <- runif(1000, -pi,pi)
x <- 16*sin(r)^3
y <- 13*cos(r)-5*cos(2*r)-2*cos(3*r)-cos(4*r)+rnorm(1000)

Solution: 

cor.test(x,y)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  x and y
## t = -0.45893, df = 998, p-value = 0.6464
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.07644984  0.04751026
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.0145256
plot(x,y)

Negative Binomial

9. simulate a negative binomial sample with r=4, p=0.3, and sample size n=10,000, and then

  • generate a histogram of the sample
  • calculate sample mean and sample variance
  • calculate theoretical mean and variance of the NB with r=4 and p=0.3

Solution: 

nbsim <- function(r, p, n){
  x <- rnbinom(n, size = r, prob=(1-p))
  hist(x, breaks=100,col="blue")
  cat("mean(x): ", mean(x), "\n")
  cat("var(x): ", var(x), "\n")
  cat("r*p/(1-p): ", r*p/(1-p), "\n")
  cat("r*p/(1-p)^2: ", r*p/(1-p)^2, "\n")
}

nbsim(4, 0.3, 10000)

## mean(x):  1.7114 
## var(x):  2.448555 
## r*p/(1-p):  1.714286 
## r*p/(1-p)^2:  2.44898

Principal Component Analysis

10. Run the following code to load the crab data and then perform PCA to condense the information contained in the continuous measurements.

data("crabs", package="MASS")
? crabs  ## data description

Solution: 

cor(crabs[,4:8])
##           FL        RW        CL        CW        BD
## FL 1.0000000 0.9069876 0.9788418 0.9649558 0.9876272
## RW 0.9069876 1.0000000 0.8927430 0.9004021 0.8892054
## CL 0.9788418 0.8927430 1.0000000 0.9950225 0.9832038
## CW 0.9649558 0.9004021 0.9950225 1.0000000 0.9678117
## BD 0.9876272 0.8892054 0.9832038 0.9678117 1.0000000
par(mfrow=c(2,3))
tmp <- lapply(4:8,function(x){hist(crabs[,x],breaks=15, xlab=names(crabs)[x], main="")})
par(mfrow=c(1,1))

apply(crabs[,4:8],2,summary)

11. Without running the following simulation code, determine how many major principal components will be generated for this simulation data if PCA is performed.

set.seed(1234)
x1 <- runif(1000)
x2 <- 1+7*x1 
x3 <- runif(1000)
x4 <- 2*x3
x5 <- runif(1000)
x6 <- runif(1000)
data <- cbind(x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6)

Solution: 4 major principal components.

data.pca <- prcomp(data, center=T, scale=T)
